6 29 Julij 1681
th
Abram tivian
London
mij last to gon ao on the 22 cois since res dyc of 13 ditto which
doth vere much troable mee, because you do not meanon one the least
oord off what I desired by mine off 1118 ditto principally abaut the bayes
haveing sold agreat mony to deliver att tharrital of pindon, vanting
noless then 50 ps off 40 a 42 sreight, as here before oreehate hadd it
3 packes could beready, 2 off themeach, with 20 keaby bayes, & 2o of the
A.H.3 greon sead you must contrire itt so that each vessel may bring no less
then 2 packe of bayes, & rather 3 for smith, now to divert our risics you might
send 2 bales of cloth, & one of bayes by way of Rotterdam on dort. I observe
my ord. to be for 5 bales of dosins of they be not already, lett come butt 4 of
prijses as these 2 al ready recd their invoyce, & the fiste of a lower sort to be
of about 3f ayd now, and amonfitt them 4 r 5 of this cullours, & att least I b
grages as N. 540, & 541 in the bale N. 62, for that cullour is realy good: I have
fiven you credit for the valew of the invoyces sent mee, butt I wonder you o not advis
mee where the goods are, & what is shipt, to gev. my self accordingly
Inclosed a bill for £100- att ½ 1so on John van ladt, & one for £80- att vr, for
boath which please bo procure the need full & pass to my acctt., I hope to rimittin
more next week. as for laces you dave sere o moenr tis answer I oss
not returnethe that are not well for they nas sell here
what you weight about the cornetts, if they will, sell, sere: as for pours I cave sont
you not pourt of france, though you would buy 2 cornetds, I know you may sava then
from france dixcetely, butt poutt de malins hom this place. m. Willingltonm
would faine have a foint cornett & laces for sleeves, I have nrott him, that you
have the sort, so see what you can do with In about one of the maline
London mr. Henry Maynard
mij last to you was on the 22½ curtt. sence reed yo of 14 d. have given you credit
for miy ½ part In the 2 bales of Herties aboard of Pindar N33 is of great
paysen, butt t is no maeser if the goods be accordingly. I am sorry to see no
1 silver marp shipt yett, & do long bo seare witl much inpase what is past
abait them, for I must dave them I take notice of yd spiculation of rifing
markers, espetally reds, so would have you take yds burne with good tine
& oppontinntie to provide one bale of reds assorted from £9„10 to £11: 10
inclosed patt. according to which you please to provide 12 p of spanish cloaches
from 8: to 11.6, thougs I would rather have non of 8, butt 9 the lowest
this I could wish to be a curious affortment, because I finde I do much
want itt to sent of the rest, Porter is well arrived: yd. bill for £200-
shall finde du donour, & be past to my acctt
Londen Eamund Warner
C 29 d
my last to you was ontle 22th curtt. sence recd yd of 14d. by which I amglad
to understand yd. good arrivall. as for the mistakes in the invoyce of N. 26
you save credit for, as I advised you bay my last you complaine of the goods sent
you, truly of the cornets do not prove well, or will not sell to content returne
them, & s'll dispose of them other vise, butt for cheape chespness, I can not beleave
any is served better, and endeed I would advise you to make a tryall of some
boddy elce, & give n att the vere same time one & the same sustine
as you do mee, & pray see then who doth best, thougs now laces ae fallen
sence yd. departure well 15 which will not contineuw longer then ot 2
Monshs att finthest, the cometts I bespooke in yd beeng bere are disposed off
otherwiye, because then I found you not to well inclined to have them yet
I ease I can finde any to yo. desire, I'll gett them & send to you, as also the
parcell for custs to yd. instrnetions, which I could save in in few dayes, did not
you limitt mee so much the breath, butt I laveing most part of my goods
out of nonnerres, begoijn lores, & from fills devotes that live within the countrey
muss exspect my turne, & then I am sure to gett the best penneworthts as
you may exspect. yd acctt. you may exspect 3 first Intrnu wee negleet
nothing in the persieuthing of the stole goods att gantt, futt the ofters are
vere haid against is, because the soldiers are all deserted, that did itt, &
they make the governor beleave that they have restored most part, r as if
wee made greather pretence as wee must have, in somuch that wee car not
procure, or gett sin consent to receave our satisfaction, which the states of
solanders dad consinted, wee impley what freinds wee car, & truly the longer
itt nunmes, the worse itt be, yett wee can butt do the uttmost
